The erroneous code fails because the String variable lacks an initial value before usage. Java requires all local variables to be initialized prior to printing or processing them. The corrected version assigns "Hello world" directly during declaration.

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String variable = "Hello world";
        System.out.println(variable);
    }
}
```

The next class assigns a fresh value to the shared variable name.

```java
public class ValueAssigner {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String variable = "New assigned text";
        System.out.println(variable);
    }
}
```

This class performs concatenation by joining the variable with extra text.

```java
public class StringConcatenator {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String variable = "Hello world";
        String result = variable + " and more";
        System.out.println(result);
    }
}
```

